{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559307/1930051501/0196.xml":{"full_text":"MARION PROGRESS\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY\nBY THE\nMcdowell publishing co.,\nMARION, N. C.\nTELEPHONE 64\nS. E. WHITTEN, Editor and Prop\nW. A. COLLETT, Associate Editor\nEntered at the Postoffice at Marion\nN. C., as second class matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\nOne Year ___$1.50\nSix Months .75\nStrictly in Advance.\nMARION, N. C., MAY 15, 193d\nHOW YOUNG ARE YOU?\nYouth ;s not a time of life\u2014it is a\nstate of mind. It is not a matter of\nripe cheeks, red lips, and supple\nknees; it is a temper of the will, a\nquality of the imagination, a vigor\nof the emotions; it is a freshness of\nthe deep springs of life.\nYouth means a temperamental\npredominance of courage over, tim\nidity, of the appetite for adventure\nover love of ease. This often exists\nin a man of fifty more than in a boy\nof twenty. Nobody grows old by\nmerely living a number of years;\npeople grow old only by deserting\ntheir ideals.\nYears wrinkle the skin, but to give\nup enthusiasm wrinkles the soul.\nWorry, doubt, self-distrust, fear\nand despair\u2014these are the long,\nlong years that bow the head and\nturn the growing spirit back to dust.\nWhether seventy or sixteen, there\nis in every being's heart the love of\nwonder, the sweet amazement at the\n\nstars and the starlike things and\nthoughts, the undaunted challenge\nof events, the unfailing childlike\nappetite for what next, and the joy\nin the game of life.\nYou are as young as your faith,\nas old as your doubt; as young as\nyour self-confidence, as old as your\nfear; as young as your hope, as old\nas your despair.\nIn the central place of your heart\nthere is a wireless station; so long\nas it receives messages of beauty,\nhope, cheer, grandeur, courage, and\npower from the earth, from men,\nand from the Infinite, so long are\nyou young. When the wires are all\ndown and the central place of your\nheart is covered with the snows of\npessimism and the ice of cynicism,\nthen are you grown old indeed.\nA LITTLE CORNER\nOF FLANDERS FIELD\nA beautiul reminder of the noble\nfellows who sleep the long sleep in\nFlanders Field was the window Dean\n*Tainter prepared for Memorial Day\n\u2014a white cross marking a grave in\na field of cool green grass splotched\nwith the poppy's blood red, .the pop\npy that now grows upon the graves\nof so many brave soldiers who\n\"went west\" in gallant company. A\nfew knew fear, some felt regret,\nperhaps; most of them died happily.\nMen of the A. E. F. who passed\nthe window, wearing a poppy in re\nmembrance of the buddies of the\n\"advanced echelon\", felt the pres\nence almost of the sleeping lads,\nwho made the supreme sacrifice. In\ntheir hearts they salutfed the men\nwho have answered the last roll\ncall, who died on the field of honor.\nNo doubt, many a shoulder was\nsquared, heads held higher, knowing\nthose who have crossed over the riv\ner would expect every man to \"car\nry on.\"\nNEW TRAFFIC LAWS\nIN EFFECT HERE\nThe attention of motorists is di\nrected to new traffic ordinances pub\nlished in this issue of The Progress.\nIt is a violation of law punishable\nby fine of $10.00, to stop a car on\nMain street between Court and\nState for a period longer than two\nminutes, except in the regular park\ning spaces.\nBy ordinance recently ratified by\nthe board of aldermen, Main, Court,\nand .Henderson streets are made\nthoroughfares. Motorists are requir\ned to come to a full stop before en\ntering these streets from a side\nstreet, each and every violation of\nthis provision constituting a sepa\nrate offense punishable by a fine of\n$5.00.\nTake notice and govern yoursel\nves accordingly.\nMR. JIMESON ANNOUNCES\nFOR COMMISSIONER\nJ. E. Jimeson, well known as a\nmember of the board of county com\nmissioners for the past two years,\nannounces this week for re-election\nto that office.\nT. L. Epley has filed with the\ncounty election board as a candidate\nfor sheriff on the Republican ticket.\nSquirrels never waste time crack\ning spoiled nuts. They are able to\ndetect the poor ones the minute they\npick them up.\nMAY POLE DANCE, FIELD DAY, MAY 9,\nMARION PUBLIC SCHOOL\nAcorn Studio Photo\nTHURSDAY MUSICALE\nAT MARION SCHOOL\nThe musicale given at the high\nschool auditorium last Thursday af\nternoon by the pupils of Misses Bur\nton and Gilkey and Mesdames Har\nris and Davis showed splendid train\ning on the part of the teachers and\ncreditable work on the part of the\nJ pupils. The program was sponsored\nby the Music Club in observance of\n1 Natiohal Music Week throughout\nthe United States.\nMrs. A. A. Morris, a member of\nthe Music Club, presented a charm\ning little Japanese operetta Friday\nmorning at the high school, while\nthe Music Club and Marion Band\nconcert was also a feature of the\nweek observed here.\nA large audience was much pleas\ned with the musicale Thursday af\nternoon, the program following:\nChorus, Joys of Spring __ Giebel\nSolo, Playing Games __ Greenwald\nJean Ellis.\nDuet, A Little Journey __ Williams\nWilma Sprinkle and Mrs. Davis.\nSolo, Cheerfulness Rowe\nSue Sweeney\nDuet, The Box of Soldiers,\nDorothy Wilkinson and Mary\nHenderson.\nSolo, By the Waters of Minnetonka,\nLieurance\nMary Margaret Giles.\nViolin Solo, Valsette Borowski\nBetty Wilson.\nSolo, Valse Caprice Newland\nHelen Klontz.\nSolo, Gretchen's Dance Linn\nMildred Craig.\nDuet, Early Morning Bilbro\nMaybelle Smith and Miss Gilkey.\nSolo, Dawn of Spring Ellis\nPlayful Kittens Lawson\nBobbie Gilkey.\nMarch de Concert Mazurette\nHiram Bishop.\nValse Styrienne Wollenhaupt\nAnna Kate Craig.\nDuet, In Schubert's Day, Krentlin\nBillie Carter and Mrs. Harris.\nSolo, Mendelssohn Spaulding\nLa Donna e Mobile, Arr. by\nWilliams,\nMargaret Wessinger.\nDuet, Coquettish Smile, Engelmann\nMargaret Wilson and Mrs. Harris.\nSpring Greeting Strauss\nEast Marion Chorus.\nMARION HOSIERY MILL\nDOING FINE BUSINESS\nBusiness in some lines continues\ngood, in fact is getting better. W.W.\nNeal, president of Marion Knitting\nMills, stated yesterday that his plant\nis manning full time, day and night,\ni and that the product is sold up to the\nfirst of September. That is to say,\nthere are orders on hand for goods\nthat will require three and one-half\nmonths to manufacture.\nMr. Neal stated that he has an or\nder from one concern for 35,000\npairs of socks, made up in two num\nbers, 25,000 of one kind and 10,000\ni of another. Which is very good evi\ndence that somebody has confidence\nin an early return of prosperity.\nThis is very encouraging. When the\nI mills run they give employment to\ni many people, who in turn pass the\nI good times on to all classes of bus\niness.\nThirty-nine farmers in Cleveland\ncounty have entered the corn grow\ning contest Reports on the progress\nof this work will be made each\nmonth to County Agent R. W.\nShoffner.\nMARION SCHOOL NEWS\n\"The Last Comet,\" an operetta,\nwill be given by thte pupils of 6B\nGrade Thursday evening, May 22,\nat 8 o'clock in the high school audi\ntorium. The main characters of the\noperetta are: James Tate, \"Sirius,\nthe Dog Star;\" Guy Little, \"Atom;\"\nand Mildred Johnson, \"Mother\nJ Earth.\" There are three choruses:\nPotentates, Mother Earth's children,\nand Rainbow Sisters. Miss Moser\nand Mrs. Morris are in charge of\nthe operetta.\nSenior examinations started to\nday, and will continue through Fri\nday and Monday. The \"exams\" for\nthe other classes will be held the\nlast three days of next week.\nThe Student Council met Monday\nfor the first time to study and pass\nupon a constitution which will gov\nern their qualifications and activi\nties. Robert Smith, president of the\ni student body, presided.\nMr. Gordon and Mr. Beam atten\nded the annual meeting: and banquet\nof the high school principals and\ncoaches held in Hickory last Friday\nnight.\n1 The big pageant, \"The Giants of\nFortune,\" Friday night of next\nj week, May 2.'), is one of the inter\nesting events of commencement\ntime.\n'Tis said that one of our fair sen\niors could not wait until after grad\nuation to wed the young man of her\nchoice. Anyway, she's married.\n\nWILL OPEN SUMMER\nSCHOOL ON JUNE 9TH\nOpening June 9th the Marion high\nschool will conduct a regular six\nweeks summer school. This school\nwill be standard in every respect\nand credits obtained during this\n(summer session will be accepted\nby any accredited high school.\nThis summer school is the first to\nbe attempted by the high school.\n1 Mr. H. F. Beam will have charge and\nany person that is interested may\nreceive detailed information by get\ning intouch with Mr. Beam.\nThis school will be in session only\nthrough the morning hours, from\neight until twelve, with no activities\nduring the afternoon. No student\nmay register for more than two sub\njects which will be a semester's\ncredit of one-half unit for each\ncourse.\nMr. Beam stated that any high\nschool subject will be taught that is\nj de nanded, provided as many as\nthree students desire the course.\nI\nI\nIMPORTANT MEETING OF\nPARENT-TEACHERS ASSOC'N\nThe last meeting of the Parent\nTeachers Association for the school\nyear will be held in fhe school audi\ntorium this.. Thursday, afternoon at\n3:30. Mrs. Jessie R. Morgan, the\nsecretary, announces that the annual\nelection of officers will cake place at\nthis time. Other matters of interest\nto all the members will be presented\nand a full attendance is urged.\nTUG OF WAR, FIELD DAY, MAY 9,\nMARION PUBLIC SCHOOL\nAcorn Studio Photo\nCOOKING MADE EASY\nELECTRICAL WAY\nSponsored by Southern Public\nUtilities Company, Mrs. Beulah\nYates conducted a two-day cooking\nclass in the Oasis theatre, attended\nby many ladies, ninety-eight being\npresent the first day, 105 the second.\nMrs. Yates demonstrated the ease of\noperation and convenience of the\nthrift cooker on a Hotpoint electric\nrange. A dinner of ham, vegetables,\nand pudding was cooked together\nwithout any mixing of flavors. An\nother cooking was boiled hamburger\nand tomatoes Attendance -prizes\nMonday were awarded to Mrs. W.\nO. Ledbetter, a Hotpoint iron; Mrs.\nJ. M. Tyler, a barbecued ham; Mrs.\nL. L. Bolch, the dinner of hamburg\ner and tomatoes; Mrs. J. G. Beaman,\nthe pudding.\nTuesday Mrs. Yates demonstrated\nthe convenience and safety of the\nautomatic temperature control,\nwhich assures constant heat at all\ntimes. A dinner of sirloin and vege\ntables was placed in the oven and\nleft the required time, when it was\ntaken out in perfect order cooked\njust right. A dinner of vegetables\nwas cooked in the thrift cooker.\nPrizes Tuesday went to Mrs. B. F.\nPollard, a Hotpoint percolator; Mrs.\nC. F. Barnes, the oven dinner; Mrs.\nj T. M. Beck the cooker dinner.\nI\nCLINCHFIELD SCHOOL\nTO GIVE PLAY MAY 20\nOn Tuesday evening, May 20th, at\n7:30 o'clock, the Seventh grade of\nthe Clinchfield School will present\nan original dramatization of Rip'\nVan Winkle.\nThe cast of characters is as fol\nlows:\nRip Van Winkle, Winfred Nor- j\nman and Clyde Crabtree.\nDame Van Winkle, Nell Condry. j\nDerrick, Earl Jolly.\nNicholas Vedder, J. C. Hensley. J\nHendrick Vedder, Buster Lee.\nJudith Van Winkle, Jean Ellis and\nGrace Robinson.\nSeth, the Inn Keeper, Paul Morgan\nThe Old Woman, Geneva Lamb, i\nHendrick Hudson, Buster Green.\nDwarfs\u2014Nellie Sparks, Ruth Jar\nrett, Margaret Green and Leila Mc\nGimsey.\nCitizens\u2014Herbert Davis, Dorothy\nDean, Nellie Sparks, Addie Sherrill\nMargaret Green, Ruth Jarrett and\nLeila McGimsey.\nMARION SCHOOL OFFICIALS\nRE-ELECTED BY BOARD\nTheir many friends and the public\ngenerally will be pleased to know\nthe Marion school board elected Su\nperintendent F. R. Richardson and\nI Principal M. W. Gordon, Jr., to\nserve in the same capacities another\nyear. In addition to efficient admin\nistration of school affairs, both these\ngentlemen take prominent parts in\nall worthwhile public affairs, social,\n1 civic, and religious, thereby making\nj themselves useful citizens whose\ngood works are known and apprecia\ni ted.\nI\nMARION REPRESENTATIVES\nAT FEDERATION MEETING\nI Representatives of women's activ\nities in Marion left Wednesday for\nPinehurst, where the State Federa-1\ni tion of Women's Clubs will be in\n(session from May 14 to 17. Two are\nj state officers, Mrs. D. F. Gil,es being\ni president of the second district while\nMrs. Annie Miller Pless is chairman\nofliterature. Miss Jeannette Gilkey\ni and Miss Mildred Hud^ins will rep\nresent the Junior Woman's Club of\nI Marion.\nPLEASANT GARDENS\nCOMMENCEMENT TUESDAY\nThe sermon to the graduating\nclass of Pleasant Gardens school will j\nbe preached Sunday morning in the\nschool auditorium, Principal R. B.\nPhilips announces.\nThe graduating exercises will take\nplace Tuesday night, the literary ad\ndress to be delivered by Dr. C. S.:\nCalfee, of Asheville Normal.\nI\nBUYING EQUIPMENT\nFOR BOYS CAMP\nE. A. Beaman, chairman, H. D.\nBishop and R. L. Greenlee, Kiwanis\ncommittee in charge of the boys\ncamp at Cove Echo, are busy with\nplans for opening the camp June 15.\nMr. Bishop has placed an order for\nnecessary equipment to be in place\nbefore the first contingent of young\ncampers arrive.\nSCOTT DAVIS\nFuneral services for Scott Davis,\nwho died in a Morganton hospital\nMonday, were held here Wednesday\nat. the home of his mother, Mrs. E.\nC. Davis, Rev. T. G. Melton in\ncharge. Interment was in East Mar\nion cemetery.\nBesides his mother, he is survived\nby several brothers and sisters of\nEast Marion.\nDon't forget WINNIE LIGHTNER\nin \"SHE COULDN'T SAY NO\" at\nMarion Theatre Thursday and Fri-1\nday. 1\nConsult Your Doctor\nYOU CAN OFTEN HEAD OFF SICKNESS\nMost serious illnesses are a long while coming on and\nmay often be headed off if only they are detected in time.\nThis is why it is so important to have your doctor and\ndentist look you over occasionally from head to foot. If\ngiven the chance, they can be depended on to save you a\ngreat deal of pain and expense.\nAnd when your doctor writes a prescription be sure to\nhave it filled by the \"Reliable Prescriptions\" drug store.\nAll your doctor's skill goes for naught unless his prescrip\ntions are compounded accurately from the best available\nmedicinal agents.\nTAINTER'S\nWe use only the best materials including the fine pharma\nceuticals of the Abbott Laboratories\nRfcLIABLy\nBest of Everything\nin Table Needs\nFresh Vegetables, Choice Fruits,\nFresh Eggs, Country Butter,\nStrained Honey,\nBest Hams and Bacon.\nFancy Groceries\nof fine quality.\nCOWAN GROCERY CO.\nPhone 85 Wrenn Bldg.\nWe're Looking for You!\nTo send your suits and dresses\nhere for expert cleaning, press\ning, dyeing and alterations.\nTHIS SHOP\nIs under it's former management\nThat specializes in\nSatisfactory Service\nTo everybody at all times.\nCome Back Home!\nMarion Dry Cleaning Works\nCHARLIE BURGIN, Proprietor 1\nWest Court St. Telephone 236\n\"~)ld Newspapers for sale at The Progress office at 5c a bundle.","height":"33256","width":"22380"}}
